value.0: Before you floats a dark cloak emblazoned with a sinister looking dagger.  Held aloft by nothing that can be seen, this object very fascinating.                                                                                                                                                                                   Shrine to Baravar Cloakshadow                                                                                                                                                                       The Sly One, Master of Illusion, Lord in Disguise, Bane of Goblinkin.  Baravar Cloakshadow is a sly, sneaky protector of gnomes. His defenses and protective strategies are rooted in deceit-illusions, traps, ambushes, and the like-and his jests and tricks may cause their victims some pain (emotional if not physical). In addition to teaching the arts of disguise, stealth, and spying to the gnomes, the Sly One creates traps and illusions of incredible depth and cunning, a skill he has passed on to gnomes
Cloak of Baravar Cloakshadow
Shrine to Baravar Cloakshadow
Door
A portal glows softly before you. You wonder where it leads.
Recall Portal

The giant statue resembles a gnome that seems to be planning mischief with his two headed battleaxe. In front, stuck to the floor, is a large nugget of pure gold. 

You are uncertain if it is the brilliantly detailed artisanship of this shrine or that there is an influental presence, but you can't help but feel humbled and amused as if someone just told you a very good joke.
Shrine to Garl Glittergold

Solitary and enigmatic as the Deepbrother himself, this star ruby dazzles more than the eyes as it calls the faithful to contemplate their own purpose.

The Deep Brother is by nature solitary and thoughtful. He rarely consorts with others, even other gnome gods. He is a benign, but secretive deity, caring only for his own people and their defense. He frequently dispatches his avatars to defend his followers from dangers of the Underdark.
Shrine to Callarduran Smoothhands

The Shield of the Golden Hills is ever vigilant in guarding against Urdlen's insidious attacks, and he battles the gods of the kobold and goblin pantheons regularly. Gaerdal Ironhand is the most dwarflike deity of the gnome pantheon, rarely smiling, and he is the only gnome god who could be considered stern. Gaerdal takes his duties as the protector of gnome burrows very seriously, at the cost of sacrificing a playful spirit. The Shield of the Golden Hills has no use for tricks, jokes, or deceits, and he remains unsmiling at gnome tales and pranks.
Shrine to Gaerdal Ironhand

Also known as The Masked Leaf, the Forest Gnome, Father of Fish and Fungus, Baervan Wildwanderer is the god of the forest gnomes.  He is revered by the svirfneblin as the Father of Fish and Fungus.

He works closely with Segojan Earthcaller, for both gods are concerned with the natural world.  Traditionally, their portfolios are divided between caring for forest animals and plants for Baervan, and burrowing animals for Segojan.
Shrine to Baervan Wildwanderer

Earthfriend, the Rock Gnome, Lord of the Burrow, Digger of Dens, the Badger, the Wolverine.

He is a friend to all living animals that move above and below the earth and one who speaks to the very rock itself. Segojan gifted rock gnomes with the ability to communicate with burrowing animals and taught them how to befriend moles, badgers, and other subterranean creatures.  Segojan is widely worshiped by those who dwell within the earth, particularly rock gnomes, and to a lesser extent, deep gnomes.
Shrine to Segojan Earthcaller

The Meddler

Nebelun the Meddler is the name by which many folk refer to Gond the Wonderbringer and is revered by the svirfnebli for his inventiveness and engineering.  Before you hangs a shining toothed wheel with four spokes cast in shiny brass that is well polished by temple priests.
Shrine to Nebulun

Master of Metal, Lord of Smiths, the Armorer, the Weaponsmith, the Great Steelsmith, the Pyromancer

Flandal is a true master craftsmen. He is ever-demanding of his own work and strives tirelessly to increase his skill. He is also a patient tutor; only lazy and indifferent craftsfolk draw his ire. The Master of Metal is often found traveling with one or two of the other gnome powers in search of new ores and veins of metal to use in his forges. When Flandal is not traveling, he can be found in his workshop, planning or making a new magical weapon. He is no stranger to battle, trusting in the creations of his forges to see him to victory.  The svirfnebli venerate Flandal in the hope of gaining a fraction of his skill.
Shrine to Flandal Steelskin
This tome appears to be well worn from much use.  In fine flowing script inside the front cover appears a name that has become unreadable over time.
Pantheons of the Underdark
On this parchment you find a requisition form for an all too large number of resurrection balms from the Brosna Temple.
Balm Requisition Form
This small hole seems to be without a bottom.  When one draws close, the fainstest sounds of digging can be heard.  There is something unwholesome about it.
Bottomless Hole

The Do's and Don'ts of Temple Portal Operations
-By Malketon Felnurd
